    <title type="text">Ancient History Teachers’ Notes</title>
    <content type="html"><![CDATA[<a
      href="http://www.jact.org/publications/ancient-history-teachers-notes/">Ancient History
      Teachers’ Notes</a><br /><blockquote class="tr_bq"><span style="font-size:
      x-small;">These teachers’ notes are intended to prepare teachers for the new OCR
      specification by covering the main aspects of each of the optional subjects. They contextualise
      the prescribed sources and identity which issues and sources are most relevant to the
      individual bullet points of the specification. They will also give relevant extra background
      information.</span> </blockquote><blockquote class="tr_bq"><span
      style="font-size: x-small;">They are designed to complement, rather than replace, the
      materials provided by OCR. The format of the notes varies depending on their authors. Those for
      AH2 options 2 and 3 are set out as schemes of work, while the others address the specific
      bullet points identified in the specification. For other week by week lesson plans/schemes of
      work, please see the support material booklets provided by OCR. Bibliographies for each of the
      options are in the Teacher support booklet.</span> </blockquote><blockquote
      class="tr_bq"><span style="font-size: x-small;">JACT Ancient History Committee<br
      />Sept 2008</span><br /> <h4><span style="font-size:
      x-small;">AH1</span></h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.jact.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/AH1-option-1-democracy.pdf">AH1 option
      1 Democracy</a></span><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.jact.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/AH1-option-2-delian-league.pdf">AH1
      option 2 Delian League</a></span><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.jact.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/AH1-option-3-Sparta.pdf">AH1 option 3
      Sparta</a></span><br /> <h4><span style="font-size:
      x-small;">AH2</span></h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.jact.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/AH2-option-1-Cicero.pdf">AH2 option 1
      Cicero</a></span><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.jact.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/AH2-option-2-Augustus.pdf">AH2 option 2
      Augustus</a></span><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.jact.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/AH2-option-3-Roman-Britain.pdf">AH2
      option 3 Roman Britain</a></span><br /> <h4><span style="font-size:
      x-small;">AH3</span></h4><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.jact.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/AH3-option-2-Conflict.pdf">AH3 option 2
      Conflict</a></span><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.jact.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/AH3-option-3-Culture-of-Athens.pdf">AH3
      option 3 Culture of Athens</a></span><br /> <h4><span
      style="font-size: x-small;">AH4</span></h4><span style="font-size:
      x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.jact.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/AH4-option-1-Republic.pdf">AH4 option 1
      Republic</a></span><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.jact.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/AH4-option-2-imperial-Rome.pdf">AH4
      option 2 Imperial Rome</a></span><span style="font-size: x-small;"><a
      href="http://www.jact.org/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/AH4-option-3-Empire.pdf">AH4 option 3
      Empire</a></span></blockquote>&nbsp; ]]></content>
